Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

In MySQL database it works like a charm. I've investigated it a bit and it seems that I got a unique constraint for following columns: `image_id`,`member`,`deleted_at`. As I get deeper I've found the migration /glance/db/sqlalchemy/migrate_repo/versions/022_image_member_index.py which changes the unique constraint from

`image_id`, `member` to `image_id`,`member`,`deleted_at` but only for mysql and postgresql. It does nothing for the ibm_db_sa, so it has more aggresive constraint.

I would suggest to prepare a new migration script (just upgrade, we do not support downgrades anymore) for ibm_db_sa to ensure the constraint is the same as in the mysql database.

Seems legit?

Patch Set 3:

@kamil, thanks for your comments, you are my first code reviewer in openstack :) 

Maybe the migration should cover db2 also. The problem now is if we don't check the deleted member record before create a new member, it will create a new one, and then we will find there would be two member records between the same image and tenant, one is marked as deleted, the other is not.
Is this a correct behavor ? I'm wondering why can't we use only one record to maintain the member-ship. Maybe there is some other consideration, I'd like to know more.

Patch Set 3:

@kamil.rykowski@intel.com, I tried to make a migration for db2, I found DB2 constraint is more restricted than mysql, in db2, the columns in unique constrains should be "NOT NULL", currently the column "deleted_at" is nullable. That means we should alter it to "not null". Besides, since the new created image-member is null for "deleted_at", so we will have to insert a default timestamp value for those existing columns.

Patch Set 3: -Code-Review

@Long Quan Sha: I have to admit that I'm not familiar with the DB2 engine, but have googled a bit and you right - unique constraint cannot be placed on nullable columns. That's pretty sad, because we need to get other workaround to fix the mentioned issue which you have reported. Basically we can't set default value for deleted_at as it determines when the membership has been deleted, and setting it to the current timestamp on creation will lead to confusion (why my newly created membership has deleted_at set-on? is it deleted or what?). Dirty hack.

The only workaround I can think of (as you have mentioned earlier) is to keep only one pair of member & image_id in the image_members table. So the simple flow will look as follows:

1. Member X is added to the image Y (deleted is 0, deleted_at is null)
2. Member X is removed from image Y (deleted is set to 1, deleted_at is current timestamp)

HINT: Right to this point, the flow is the same as in the current implementation.

3. Member X is again added to the image Y. Instead of creating a new record we simply get the deleted one and sets the deleted flag to 0 again and erase the deleted_at to be null again.

_______

The only caveat is that we don't store the membership history anymore, but do we really need to know that given member has been associated with the image 10 times (9 deleted rows + 1 non-deleted)? Need further discussion with our cores.

Abhishek, I did the change as your example provided in patch18, but the unit test failed in patch 20. That made me think twice about this line,I think the original line is correct. Let's explain:

if include_deleted is True, what we want is all records including the deleted, so don't need to filter anything.

if we use query = query.filter_by(deleted=include_deleted), then it becomes query.filter_by(deleted=True) in this case, it will just leave records which are not marked with deleted.

It is interesting, it proves the value of unit test. That also makes me believe unit test is very necessary. :)
